author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Sudan's paramilitary the Rapid Support Forces (RSF), which has been accused of committing atrocities in Darfur, says it has now agreed to a humanitarian truce.  
The pause was proposed in September by a group known as the Quad - that's made up of the US, Egypt, the UAE and Saudi Arabia. 
The proposal includes a three-month humanitarian pause followed by a permanent ceasefire and a nine-month transition to civilian rule.
More than a week ago, the RSF seized el-Fasher, the army's last stronghold in Darfur. 
Accounts of mass killings, rape, torture and humiliation have since been reported by those who escaped.

Al Jazeera’s Hiba Morgan has more from Khartoum, Sudan. 

Khalid Mishain is a spokesman for the Youth Citizen Observers Network, an organization that monitors the human rights and humanitarian situation in Sudan.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Governments around the world now owe nearly $100 trillion in public debt. That's almost double what they owed just a decade ago.

The International Monetary Fund warns that by 2029, global debt will surpass 100 percent of the world's gross domestic product, meaning the world's borrowing could soon exceed the size of the entire global economy.

But there is a stark contrast: Richer nations can - for now - still borrow at lower costs and keep spending while many poorer nations are running out of room to take on more debt.

When borrowing becomes too big who pays the price?

description:

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israel has targeted every source of Palestinian livelihood across Gaza, including its once-thriving fishing industry. Before the war, Gaza’s fishermen hauled in more than 4,600 tonnes of fish each year, despite facing the constant risk of being detained, killed, or injured by Israeli forces. Since the war began, most of their boats have been destroyed, and those casting their nets a few metres from the shore have come under Israeli fire. In January, Israel declared Gaza’s waters a 'no-go zone,' banning fishing, swimming, and any access to the sea. Gaza has since lost 94 percent of its catch, cutting off one of the last remaining sources of food.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim Al Khalili reports from Gaza City.

description:
The Trump administration's tariff policies are being challenged in the Supreme Court. It heard arguments on Wednesday—saying the White House had overstepped its authority in imposing levies without input from Congress. If the challenge is successful, tariff payments may need to be refunded. But the Trump administration could use other legal measures to keep the policy in place.

Al Jazeera’s Patty Culhane reports from Washington, DC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The US government shutdown is now in its 36th day—a record-breaking length. While both political parties blame each other for the stalemate, the result is being felt by the American public. Hundreds of thousands of federal workers are going without pay, and government programs like food benefits have been slashed. Flight cancellations have also been announced at dozens of US airports, with air traffic controllers on reduced hours.

Al Jazeera’s Rosiland Jordan reports from Capitol Hill on the persistent deadlock.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Leaders from more than 150 countries are beginning to arrive in Belem in northern Brazil. They’ll be attending a Climate Summit ahead of the formal start of the UN COP30 conference, and for the first time, both summits are being held in the Amazon rainforest. However, US President Donald Trump, who has pulled out of the Paris Climate Agreement, says neither he nor any high-level US official will attend. 

Al Jazeera’s Latin America Editor Lucia Newman reports from Belem.
